##"Herd Immunity, " past lives

Lifeweek

By Yuan Yue

An epidemic in its natural state

In a news conference on Thursday, the Prime Minister, Boris Johnson, announced his government's anti-disease policy, immediately putting the concept of "herd immunity" on the map. What does that even mean? How is it different from our epidemic prevention policy? This starts with some of the basic characteristics of infectious diseases.

By Yuan Yue

An epidemic in its natural state

When a person has an acute infectious disease, in most cases there are only two outcomes: Death or immunity. The former is easy to understand, the latter refers to the infected person's immune system "recognize" the pathogen, the next time it will not be caught.

Only in rare cases do acute infections become chronic, such as when HIV is retranscribed into DNA and integrated into the host genome, or the hepatitis B virus enters a liver cell and transforms into "covalently closed circular DNA" (CCCDNA) , hiding in the nucleus of the host cell. Both cases are rare and will not be discussed in this article.

Neither death nor immunity happens immediately after infection, but over time. During this time, the infected person becomes the source of infection, helping the pathogen find its next host. An infected person's ability to infect others can be measured by a "Basic reproduction number" (R0) . If R0 is greater than 1, over time, the disease will spread throughout the population.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Imagine a small, isolated human community, and when a pathogen spreads to everyone, there's only one way it can go, and that's extinction. In fact, this is the ultimate fate of most human pathogens in primitive societies.

That changed when the population ballooned and cities finally appeared on earth. Because of the large population, there are babies born in cities all the time, which is the equivalent of providing a steady stream of new hosts for the pathogen, which finally sees the promise of eternal life.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In this case, the outcome of each pathogen depends on its R0 value and the population of the enclosed community. According to calculations, even for measles with an R0 of 12-18, a closed community with a population of less than 500,000 can not survive forever.

Unfortunately, with the expansion of cities and the expansion of human migration routes, most human infectious diseases can easily find new hosts and continue to spread among human populations, this was the human condition before modern medicine.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Humans were not masters of microbes at the time, and both sides maintained an equal relationship of struggle and mutual benefit. On the one hand, pathogens are becoming more benign as they continue to infect humans. On the other hand, the human immune system becomes stronger and stronger under the selective pressure of various pathogens, and the probability of acquiring lifelong immunity immediately after a minor illness after infection continues to increase, that's why the human species is alive today.

However, this natural process is bound to accompany the old and infirm death and elimination. This is not a problem for any group of wild animals. The problem is that the evolution of higher intelligence, emotional patterns and moral norms that are uniquely human, and in particular the emergence of humanitarianism, have fundamentally changed the way we view natural selection.

The emergence of vaccines is a direct result of this shift in attitude.

Vaccines and herd immunity

In the 18th century, a British physician named Edward Jenner invented the Vaccinia vaccine, revolutionizing the relationship between humans and viruses.

A vaccine is essentially an inactivated (or inactivated) virus that is artificially propagated through a population that is rapidly immunized by most of the population, thus got rid of the virus for the human "natural" selection.

So how many people in a closed community need to be immunized to stop the virus from spreading? That's where the mathematicians come in. Mathematicians soon developed an algorithm that, knowing the R0 value of a human virus, could calculate the minimum immunity needed to stop it spreading.

In general, the higher the R0 of a virus, the higher the minimum immunity required. Measles, for example, has a minimum immunization rate of about 95% , meaning that 95% of the population is vaccinated before the disease is stopped.

The above calculation is more than just a mathematical game; it has practical applications. You know, vaccines don't work for everyone. Vaccines Do not protect newborns, vulnerable people with weakened immune systems, or people who, for other reasons, do not have access to antibodies, such as allergies to vaccines.

So how do we protect these people? The answer is Community Immunity. This concept is essentially the "minimum immunization rate" mentioned above. It was originally an academic concept in the field of epidemiology, but when vaccines were widely used to fight large-scale infectious diseases, the concept has taken on a new life.

Herd Immunity has a more popular English name, which literally translates to Herd Immunity. The people who first coined the term clearly confused humans with livestock, and the two were indeed indistinguishable for epidemiological studies. But the subsequent popularity of the concept proved that humans and cattle are different, because cattle don't have to worry about getting old or sick, whereas humans do. Humanitarian decision we will not voluntarily give up to protect anyone, even if he is a little "genetic value" of the old and infirm. Herd immunity is the only way to protect these people. It requires each of us to make a small sacrifice in exchange for the safety of the sick and the old.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
As mentioned above, a vaccine is an inactivated (or inactivated) virus, which is inherently risky. The reason we call vaccines a good thing, is because the benefits of vaccines outweigh the risks, not because they're all good and no harm. For example, more than 10 billion doses of the deactivated polio vaccine have been used worldwide since 2000, which is the equivalent of preventing 6 million polio cases, although 580 children became ill in the process, but on the whole it is cost-effective, and that is the true humanitarianism based on science.

The value of mass immunization is that the widespread use of the polio vaccine protects the small number of people who can not be vaccinated for some reason. But because vaccines can be a little dangerous, some "smart" parents have come up with all sorts of reasons not to vaccinate their children. This is not a problem for his children, but if there are more such parents, mass immunization will not be sustainable, which is why mass immunization programmes in public health are mandatory, this is typical state behavior. At the same time, the state must guarantee the quality of the vaccine, the accident must be fully compensated, this is the state must bear the responsibility.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In short, the core idea of mass immunization is to protect the elderly, the sick and the disabled. As a healthy adult, you must realize that you are not only a victim of an epidemic, but also a carrier of it, the most dangerous role you can play.

Population immunity and novel coronavirus

So can herd immunity help us fight the new crown disease? The answer depends on what the information is. The new coronavirus is a completely new pathogen, and our understanding of the virus is constantly updated, and our epidemic prevention policies will change accordingly. This is a common situation and there is no need to make a fuss, let alone resort to conspiracy theories.

For example, the British government's strategy changed a day after Prime Minister Johnson's speech on "mass immunization" , announcing that mass rallies would be banned from next week, this is probably because many British ngos are already doing it on their own.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Boris was joined at Thursday's press conference by Sir Pattrick Valeins, the government's chief scientific adviser, and Dr Chris Whitty, the government's chief medical adviser. The idea, presumably, is that Boris did not come up with the government's epidemic prevention policy by himself, but rather made scientific adjustments based on existing knowledge of virology.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
So what have British scientists found that is different from others?

First, British scientists estimate that between 5,000 and 10,000 people are infected in the UK. The number is much higher than the published number of confirmed cases, simply because the testing technology can not keep up.

Second, British scientists believe the main victims of the disease are the elderly, as well as middle-aged and elderly people with other serious chronic diseases. For the majority of healthy young and middle-aged people, the mortality rate of this disease is less than 1% , within the acceptable range.

Third, British scientists believe that the virus is far more contagious than SARS, and that most infections are caused by people who are asymptomatic or have mild pre infection, which makes prevention and control extremely difficult.

There seems to be a big gap between the three new findings and what most Chinese people think about the new crown disease, especially the first one, which contrasts sharply with the declining number of newly diagnosed cases in the country. However, given the number of celebrities and politicians being recruited abroad, this gloomy prediction by British scientists seems to make some sense.

Because of this, British scientists are giving the opposite advice to us. For example, they thought that since they could not prevent the spread of the disease, they might as well change their strategy and stop focusing on the spread of the disease and move on to the next phase, which is mainly to reduce losses, waiting patiently for two things to happen: First, waiting for a specific drug or vaccine specifically for the new crown to be developed as soon as possible; and second, it is expected that more and more healthy young and middle-aged people will be able to develop immunity through new coronaviruses, thus establishing a group immunity barrier to protect those most at risk.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Interestingly, a number of western and northern European countries, including Germany, have adopted a similar strategy to that of the UK, presumably for similar reasons. German Chancellor Merkl, for example, warned a few days ago that, according to experts'estimates, 60 to 70 percent of the German population could be infected with the new crown, echoing the predictions of British scientists.

Many chinese-language media have referred to the epidemic prevention policies of countries such as the UK and Singapore as "Buddhism" , which is a bit frivolous. It conceals the crucial fact that national circumstances vary from country to country, and that the scientific knowledge of scientists varies slightly from country to country, and that it is perfectly normal to adopt different coping strategies.

It is also worth arguing that British politicians believe more in Nudge than Force as the best way to promote any policy. The idea comes from a 2009 best-selling book by Richard Taylor, an American economist, and CASS Sunstein, an American political scientist, with plenty of real-life examples, trying to prove that it is only through well-designed inducements and seemingly positive incentives that ordinary people can change their behaviour from the bottom of their hearts.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In the case of the new crown, British scientists believe the virus will not disappear from the earth like SARS, but will continue to make a comeback like the flu. If that is the case, then forcing people to stay in isolation for long periods of time is not realistic, and sooner or later it will lead to a backlash that will eventually spiral out of control. If so, it might as well do not limit, to use other milder way to persuade people to take the initiative to make reasonable epidemic prevention behavior, in order to slow down the spread of the virus.

It must be pointed out here that the British government's approach has met with opposition from many experts, including many British scholars. Writing in the Guardian, for example, Tony Yetts, a former economist at the University of Birmingham in the United Kingdom, argues that the theory of boosting is based on past experience and may no longer be able to adapt to current conditions. The British government's approach, for example, is different from that of many other countries, and contrary to the advice of the World Health Organization, is likely to be counterproductive.

Conclusion

Will the British government's epidemic prevention policy really work? No one knows for sure, because no one knows whether the new coronavirus will have genetic mutations or not, and whether the case-fatality rate of young and middle-aged people will remain at a very low level, and the ability of the UK health system to cope with a possible emergency surge.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
AGAIN: perhaps we should not rush to conclusions about such a new epidemic, but rather encourage countries to respond differently according to their own national circumstances. This would at least provide scientists with a few more control groups to help future humans find more efficient ways to cope.

And that... is the higher order of humanity.
